1 SECTION 1. IC 10-17-16 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 16. Prohibition of Receiving Compensation for
5 Assisting a Person in Obtaining Veterans' Benefits
6 Sec. 1. This chapter does not apply to:
7 (1) a representative of a recognized organization;
8 (2) an agent; or
9 (3) an attorney;
10 accredited under 38 CFR 14.629 (as in effect July 1, 2025).
11 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "compensation" means the
12 payment of:
13 (1) money;
14 (2) a thing of value; or
15 (3) a financial benefit.
16 Sec. 3. As used in this chapter, "person" means:
17 (1) an individual;
2026 IN 231—LS 6559/DI 116

2
1 (2) a corporation;
2 (3) a business trust;
3 (4) an estate;
4 (5) a trust;
5 (6) a partnership;
6 (7) a limited liability company;
7 (8) an association;
8 (9) a joint venture;
9 (10) a public corporation;
10 (11) a government or governmental subdivision, agency, or
11 instrumentality; or
12 (12) any other legal or commercial entity.
13 Sec. 4. As used in this chapter, "veterans' benefits matter"
14 means the preparation, presentation, or prosecution of any claim
15 affecting any person who has filed, or expressed an intent to file, a
16 claim for any benefit, program, service, commodity, function,
17 status, or entitlement for which veterans, their dependents, their
18 survivors, or any other individuals are eligible under the laws and
19 regulations administered by the United States Department of
20 Veterans Affairs or the United States Department of Defense
21 pertaining to veterans, their dependents, their survivors, and any
22 other individual eligible for those benefits.
23 Sec. 5. A person may not do the following:
24 (1) Receive compensation for:
25 (A) the preparation, presentation, or prosecution of; or
26 (B) advising, consulting, or assisting an individual
27 regarding;
28 a veterans' benefits matter, except as permitted under federal
29 law.
30 (2) Receive compensation for referring an individual to
31 another person to:
32 (A) prepare;
33 (B) present, prosecute, or advise on; or
34 (C) consult or assist the individual regarding;
35 a veterans' benefits matter.
36 (3) Receive, with respect to an individual's veterans' benefits
37 matter, compensation for services rendered before the date on
38 which a notice of disagreement, decision review, or appeal is
39 filed, whichever occurs first.
40 (4) Guarantee, either directly or by implication, that any
41 individual is certain to receive specific veterans' benefits or
42 that any individual is certain to receive a specific level,
2026 IN 231—LS 6559/DI 116

3
1 percentage, or amount of veterans' benefits.
2 (5) Receive excessive or unreasonable fees as compensation
3 for the preparation, presentation, or prosecution of, or
4 advising, consulting, or assisting an individual regarding a
5 veterans' benefits matter. The factors articulated in 38 CFR
6 14.636 (as in effect January 1, 2025) govern the determination
7 of whether a fee is excessive or unreasonable.
8 (6) Condition repayment of fees:
9 (A) upon the opening of a joint account with the recipient
10 of veterans' benefits from which the person may make
11 withdrawals;
12 (B) upon the use of electronic funds transfers (as defined in
13 15 U.S.C. 1693a(7)); or
14 (C) by requiring an individual to act, in any manner, in
15 violation of 12 CFR 1005.10(c)(1), regardless of whether
16 the provision would otherwise be applicable to the
17 transaction.
18 (7) Collect, or attempt to collect, any fee for services rendered
19 after receipt of benefits by a veteran, the veteran's
20 dependents, the veteran's survivors, or any other individual
21 eligible for the benefits, if the person participated in the
22 veterans' benefits matter prior to the issuance of veterans'
23 benefits, and if the transaction was structured with an intent
24 to avoid any of the prohibitions of this chapter. There is a
25 rebuttable presumption that any collection, or attempted
26 collection, of the fees was in violation of this chapter.
27 Sec. 6. A person seeking to receive compensation for:
28 (1) the preparation, presentation, or prosecution of; or
29 (2) advising, consulting, or assisting an individual regarding;
30 a veterans' benefits matter shall, before rendering any services,
31 enter into a written agreement signed by both parties that adheres
32 to all criteria specified in 38 CFR 14.636 (as in effect July 1, 2025),
33 including all terms regarding the individual's payment of fees for
34 services rendered.
35 Sec. 7. (a) A person may not advise or assist for compensation
36 any individual concerning any veterans' benefits matter without
37 clearly providing, at the outset of the business relationship, the
38 following disclosure, both orally and in writing:
39 "This business is not sponsored by, or affiliated with, the
40 United States Department of Veterans Affairs or any other
41 federally chartered veterans' service organization. Other
42 organizations, including the Indiana Department of Veterans'
2026 IN 231—LS 6559/DI 116

4
1 Affairs, your local county veterans service officer, and other
2 federally chartered veterans' service organizations, may be
3 able to provide you with this service free of charge. Products
4 or services offered by this business are not necessarily
5 endorsed by any of these organizations. You may qualify for
6 other veterans' benefits beyond the benefits for which you are
7 receiving services here.".
8 The written disclosure shall appear in a least 12 point type and
9 shall appear in a readily noticeable and identifiable place in the
10 person's agreement with the individual seeking services. The
11 individual shall verbally acknowledge understanding of the oral
12 disclosure and shall sign the document in which the written
13 disclosure appears to represent understanding of these provisions.
14 The person offering services shall retain a copy of the written
15 disclosure while providing veterans' benefits services for
16 compensation to the individual and for at least one (1) year after
17 the date on which the services relationship terminates.
18 (b) A person may not advertise for compensation services in
19 veterans' benefits matters without including the following
20 disclosure:
21 "This business is not sponsored by, or affiliated with, the
22 United States Department of Veterans Affairs, the Indiana
23 Department of Veterans' Affairs, or any other federally
24 chartered veterans' service organization. Other organizations,
25 including the Indiana Department of Veterans' Affairs, your
26 local county veterans' service officer, and other federally
27 chartered veterans' service organizations, may be able to
28 provide you with these services free of charge. Products or
29 services offered by this business are not necessarily endorsed
30 by any of these organizations. You may qualify for other
31 veterans' benefits beyond the benefits that this business offers
32 through its services.".
33 If the advertisement is printed, including advertisements visible on
34 the Internet, the disclosure shall appear in a readily visible place
35 on the advertisement. If the advertisement is verbal, the statement
36 of the disclosure shall be clear and intelligible.
37 Sec. 8. A violation of this chapter constitutes a deceptive act
38 under IC 24-5-0.5.
39 Sec. 9. A violation of this chapter in connection with a senior
40 customer (as defined in IC 24-4.6-6-3(5)) constitutes a violation
41 under IC 24-4.6-6.
42 Sec. 10. If any clause, sentence, paragraph, or part of this
